'\" t
.\" wireguardrtc.8 -- manual page for the WireGuard RTC hole-punching daemon
.\" Process with: groff -man -Tpdf wireguardrtc.8 > wireguardrtc.pdf
.\"              or: man ./wireguardrtc.8
.\"
.TH WIREGUARDRTC 8 "2026-05-03" "wireguardrtc" "System Manager's Manual"
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH NAME
.\"
wireguardrtc \- WireGuard NAT hole-punching daemon via PeerJS signalling
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH SYNOPSIS
.\"
.SY wireguardrtc
.OP \-\-config FILE
.OP \-\-peers\-dir DIR
.OP \-\-log\-level LEVEL
.YS
.SY wireguardrtc
.B \-\-show\-config
.OP \-\-iface IFACE
.YS
.SY wireguardrtc
.B \-\-enroll\-token NAME
.OP \-\-expires SECONDS
.OP \-\-iface IFACE
.YS
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH DESCRIPTION
.\"
.B wireguardrtc
maintains direct UDP tunnels between WireGuard peers that are located
behind cone NATs (full-cone, address-restricted, or port-restricted).
It does not require a VPN relay or any static public IP address on
either end of the tunnel.
.PP
The daemon operates by:
.IP 1. 4
Discovering the host's current public IPv4 address via STUN.
.IP 2. 4
Encrypting that address (together with the WireGuard listen port and a
freshness timestamp) using a key derived from the two endpoints'
WireGuard Curve25519 identities.
.IP 3. 4
Delivering the encrypted blob to the remote peer through a
.I PeerJS
signalling broker, using the standard PeerJS OFFER wire format.
.IP 4. 4
Punching a NAT pinhole from the local WireGuard listen port toward
the remote endpoint using a raw IP+UDP packet (source-port spoofed to
the WG listen port).
.IP 5. 4
Waking the kernel WireGuard module by sending a datagram through the
WG interface, causing it to initiate a handshake to the newly
established endpoint.
.PP
Configuration is split between a single global file and per-peer
drop-in files.  Peers without a drop-in file are silently ignored,
allowing gradual adoption in mixed deployments.
.PP
The daemon is a single-file Python 3 asyncio program installed as
.IR /usr/sbin/wireguardrtc .
It runs under systemd as the
.B wireguardrtc
system user with
.BR CAP_NET_ADMIN " and " CAP_NET_RAW
capabilities; it does not require root.  Running as root is also
supported.
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH OPTIONS
.\"
.TP
.BI \-\-config " FILE"
Path to the global configuration file.
.br
Default:
.I /etc/wireguardrtc/wireguardrtc.conf
.br
Override with the environment variable
.B WIREGUARDRTC_CONFIG_DIR
(sets the directory; the filename
.I wireguardrtc.conf
is appended).
.\"
.TP
.BI \-\-peers\-dir " DIR"
Directory containing per-peer drop-in files
.RI ( "*.conf" ).
.br
Default:
.I /etc/wireguardrtc/peers.d
.\"
.TP
.BI \-\-lock\-file " PATH"
Path to the single-instance lock file.
.br
Default:
.I /run/wireguardrtc/lock
.br
Override with the environment variable
.BR WIREGUARDRTC_LOCK_FILE .
.br
The default path is created and owned by the systemd
.B RuntimeDirectory
mechanism when the unit is started; running the daemon manually as a
non-systemd-managed user requires picking a writable path here.  This
option is also useful for running multiple daemon instances on the
same host (for testing or per-namespace deployments) — each instance
must use a distinct lock path or they will refuse to start, citing
.IR "another wireguardrtc daemon already holds <path>" .
.\"
.TP
.BI \-\-log\-level " LEVEL"
Logging verbosity.  One of
.BR DEBUG ", " INFO ", " WARNING ", " ERROR .
.br
Default:
.B INFO
(overridable with the environment variable
.BR LOG_LEVEL ).
.\"
.TP
.B \-\-show\-config
Print this peer's WireGuard identity and PeerJS broker IDs, then
exit.  For each configured peer, also prints a ready-to-paste
.I peers.d
drop-in that the remote host should use to point back at this one.
.PP
.RS
Use this command on both peers to diagnose configuration mismatches:
the
.I broker-id
shown under
.B THIS PEER
on host A must equal the
.I broker-id
shown for the corresponding peer entry on host B, and vice versa.
If the broker IDs don't match despite a common
.B Salt
value, the
.B PublicKey
in one of the drop-in files is wrong.
.PP
This option does not start the daemon, does not acquire the lock file,
and does not require
.BR CAP_NET_RAW .
It does need
.B CAP_NET_ADMIN
(or root) to read WireGuard public keys from the kernel.
.RE
.\"
.TP
.BI \-\-iface " IFACE"
Used together with
.BR \-\-show\-config " or " \-\-enroll\-token .
Restrict operation to the single WireGuard interface named
.IR IFACE .
For
.BR \-\-show\-config ,
without this option all WireGuard interfaces are shown.
For
.BR \-\-enroll\-token ,
this option chooses which interface's public key is embedded in the
generated URI; required when the host has multiple WireGuard
interfaces.
.PP
.RS
Run
.B \-\-show\-config \-\-iface wg0p4
on both ends and compare the output line by line to spot key or
broker-id mismatches.
.RE
.\"
.TP
.BI \-\-enroll\-token " NAME"
Mint a single-use enrollment token for the peer named
.IR NAME ,
print the
.B wgrtc-enroll://v1?\&...
URI to standard output, render a terminal QR code if standard output
is a TTY and
.BR qrencode (1)
is installed, then exit.  See
.B AUTO\-ENROLLMENT
below for details on the protocol and the URI format.
.PP
.RS
.B Enrollment must be enabled
in
.IB CONFIG_DIR /wireguardrtc.conf
under
.B [Enrollment]
.BR "Enabled = yes" ,
with
.B ProvisionScript
pointing at an executable hook (see
.BR \-\-iface " and " "[Enrollment]" ).
.RE
.\"
.TP
.BI \-\-expires " SECONDS"
Used together with
.BR \-\-enroll\-token .
Token lifetime in seconds; valid range
.BR 60 .. 604800
(1 minute to 7 days).
.br
Default:
.B 600
(10 minutes).
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH CONFIGURATION FILES
.\"
.SS Global configuration \(em wireguardrtc.conf
.\"
The global configuration file uses INI format (parsed by Python's
.BR configparser ).
Key names are case-sensitive; base64 values are preserved verbatim.
.PP
.B [Global]
.RS
.\"
.TP
.B Salt = \fIstring\fR
.B Required.
A site-specific random string shared by all hosts that participate in
the same signalling domain.  The salt is incorporated into the PeerJS
routing ID derivation; peers with different salts cannot find each
other on the broker even if they share the same WireGuard public key.
.br
Both sides of every tunnel
.I must
use the same salt.
.br
Generate with:
.IP
.EX
head \-c 32 /dev/urandom | base64
.EE
.IP
The daemon refuses to start if Salt is absent or still set to the
placeholder value
.IR CHANGE_ME_TO_A_SECURE_RANDOM_STRING .
.\"
.TP
.B PeerJsServer = \fIwss://host/path\fR
WebSocket URL of the PeerJS signalling broker.
.br
Default:
.I wss://0.peerjs.com/peerjs
(the public PeerJS broker).
.br
For private deployments, self-host the
.B peerjs-server
Docker image and point this setting at
.IR ws://your.host:9000/peerjs .
.\"
.TP
.B PeerJsKey = \fIstring\fR
The PeerJS application key.  Must match the key configured on the
broker.
.br
Default:
.I peerjs
(matches the public broker's default).
.\"
.TP
.B PublicIp = \fIA.B.C.D\fR
.I Optional.
A static IPv4 address that overrides STUN discovery.  When set, the
daemon advertises this address in OFFERs without querying any STUN
server.  Useful on:
.RS
.IP \(bu 4
hosts with a known static public IPv4 (VPS, anycast, dedicated IP),
.IP \(bu 4
isolated network segments where outbound STUN is firewalled,
.IP \(bu 4
test fabrics where the host has no internet egress.
.RE
.IP
The value must be a valid IPv4 address that is not loopback,
multicast, link-local, unspecified, or otherwise reserved.  IPv6
endpoint publication is not implemented; use the underlying WireGuard
configuration directly if you need an IPv6 endpoint.
.IP
Default: unset (use STUN).
.RE
.PP
.B [Stun]
.RS
.TP
.B Servers = \fIhost:port\fR\fR[, \fIhost:port\fR ...]
Comma-separated list of STUN server endpoints.  The daemon queries
them in order and uses the first response.  Ignored when
.B PublicIp
is set in the
.B [Global]
section.
.br
Default:
.IR stun.l.google.com:19302 ,
.IR stun.cloudflare.com:3478 ,
.IR stun.nextcloud.com:3478
.TP
.B Strict = \fIyes|no\fR
When
.BR yes ,
STUN responses whose XOR-MAPPED-ADDRESS is not globally routable
(RFC 1918 private, CGN 100.64/10, loopback, link-local, RFC 5737
documentation, multicast, etc.) are rejected and the daemon tries
the next server in the list.  Useful when you know the host has a
real public IPv4 address and a hijacked or misconfigured STUN server
would otherwise feed you an internal address that you'd advertise to
peers as the host's endpoint.
.br
Default:
.B no
(LAN-only deployments legitimately advertise private addresses).
.RE
.PP
.B [Enrollment]
.RS
This section is read only when auto-enrollment is in use.  See the
.B AUTO\-ENROLLMENT
section below for the full protocol description.  In a deployment that
only uses pre-shared peer keys (the original v0.1 model), leave the
section out entirely.
.\"
.TP
.B Enabled = \fIyes|no\fR
Enable the auto-enrollment handler.  When
.BR yes ,
the daemon listens for
.B ENROLL
messages on its PeerJS connection and processes them via the
configured
.BR ProvisionScript .
When
.BR no
(or absent), incoming
.B ENROLL
messages are silently dropped.
.br
Default:
.B no
.\"
.TP
.B ProvisionScript = \fIPATH\fR
Path to an executable that is invoked to add a newly-enrolled peer.
The script is called as:
.IP
.EX
ProvisionScript IFACE NAME PUBKEY_BASE64
.EE
.IP
and must exit
.B 0
on success.  After a successful exit, the daemon reads back the
peer's allocated address via
.BR "wg show \fIIFACE\fR allowed-ips" .
.br
.B Required when Enabled = yes.
.IP
.B Default and recommended value:
.IR /usr/sbin/wireguardrtc-provision-client .
This is a thin wrapper that hands the request to the privileged
.BR wireguardrtc-provision-broker (8)
over a Unix socket; the broker then invokes the actual provisioning
helper with root privileges.  The broker exists because the daemon
runs heavily sandboxed (see
.B SECURITY
below) and cannot itself write to
.IR /etc/wireguard
or run privileged tooling.  Configure which helper the broker invokes
in
.IR /etc/wireguardrtc/provision-broker.conf ;
two helpers ship with this package:
.RS
.IP \(bu 4
.IR /usr/sbin/wireguardrtc-provision-default
\(em allocates from a CIDR pool defined in
.IR /etc/wireguardrtc/provisioning.conf
and writes a
.B [Peer]
block to
.IR /etc/wireguard/IFACE.conf .
.IP \(bu 4
A custom helper of your own (Ansible-managed peers, the
.IR add-peer / show-peer
helper-script family used by some private deployments, etc.).
.RE
.IP
Do
.B not
point ProvisionScript directly at the helper unless you have also
relaxed the daemon's sandbox to allow filesystem access \(em the
default helpers all write to
.IR /etc/wireguard/ ,
which the daemon's
.B ProtectSystem=strict
forbids.  See the
.B SECURITY
section below for the privilege-separation rationale.
.\"
.TP
.B StateDir = \fIPATH\fR
Directory holding the daemon's persistent enrollment state, in
particular the
.I pending-tokens.json
file.  The directory is created with mode
.B 0700
on first use.
.br
Default:
.IR /var/lib/wireguardrtc .
.\"
.TP
.B MaxPendingTokens = \fIN\fR
Refuse to mint additional tokens once
.I N
unconsumed tokens are already pending; admin must wait for them to be
used or to expire.  Bounds worst-case state size and per-ENROLL
decryption cost.
.br
Default:
.B 32
(range
.BR 1 .. 1000 ).
.\"
.TP
.B AutoActive = \fIyes\fR|\fIno\fR
When a peer completes enrollment, automatically write a
peers.d-style drop-in for it to
.IR <StateDir>/auto-enrolled.d/ .
The drop-in carries
.B Mode = active
so the daemon pushes signalling OFFERs (with the daemon's current
STUN-discovered IPv4) to the new peer without requiring you to
hand-author
.IR /etc/wireguardrtc/peers.d/<label>.conf .
This is what lets the Phase-2 long-lived listener on the Android
client follow your server's roaming public IP between sessions.
.br
An explicit drop-in in
.I /etc/wireguardrtc/peers.d/
with the same
.B PublicKey
always wins over the auto-active entry, so you can override any
specific peer (e.g. downgrade to
.B passive
or
.BR ignore ).
.br
Set this to
.B no
if you want strict admin opt-in for every peer's OFFER push.
.br
Default:
.BR yes .
.RE
.\"
.SS Per-peer drop-ins \(em peers.d/*.conf
.\"
Each file in the peers directory describes one remote WireGuard peer.
The filename (without the
.I .conf
suffix) is used as a human-readable label in log output; it has no
functional significance.  The actual peer identity comes from the
.B PublicKey
field inside the file.
.PP
Files are parsed with the same INI parser as the global config
(case-sensitive keys).
.PP
.B [Peer]
.RS
.\"
.TP
.B PublicKey = \fIbase64\fR
.B Required.
The WireGuard public key of the remote peer, in standard base64
encoding.  The daemon matches this against the live kernel state
returned by
.BR "wg show" .
.\"
.TP
.B Mode = active | passive | dns-roam | ignore
Controls how the daemon behaves for this peer.
.br
Default:
.B passive
(if the field is absent or unrecognised).
.br
See
.B PEER MODES
below for a full description.
.\"
.TP
.B DnsHost = \fIhostname:port\fR
Applicable only when
.B Mode = dns-roam.
The hostname is resolved to an IPv4 address every poll cycle; if the
resolved address differs from the current WireGuard endpoint the
kernel is updated with
.BR "wg set" .
The daemon refuses to load a
.B dns-roam
peer that omits this field.
.RE
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH PEER MODES
.\"
.TP
.B active
The daemon proactively monitors the tunnel.  Every poll cycle it
reads
.B latest-handshakes
from the kernel; if the most recent handshake is older than
.B HANDSHAKE_DEAD_THRESHOLD
(180 seconds \(em the WireGuard rekey interval of 120 s plus a 60 s
grace period) the tunnel is considered dead and the daemon sends a
PeerJS OFFER carrying this host's current public endpoint.  On
receiving the OFFER the remote peer punches its NAT and updates
its kernel endpoint, causing a fresh handshake.
.sp
Outbound OFFERs are rate-limited with exponential backoff starting at
30 seconds and capped at 300 seconds per peer.
.sp
In addition to proactive polling,
.B active
peers also respond to incoming OFFERs when the tunnel is down: the
daemon sends its own current endpoint back immediately, so both sides
can punch their respective NATs concurrently.  This cuts cold-start
latency in active-active configurations from up to one full backoff
cycle to a few seconds.
.sp
Use
.B active
for server-to-server tunnels and for any peer that is expected to be
persistently online.
.\"
.TP
.B passive
The daemon never initiates outbound PeerJS signalling for this peer.
However, when an incoming OFFER arrives from the remote peer and the
tunnel is down, the daemon automatically responds with its own current
endpoint.  This allows the remote peer to punch its NAT toward this
host even when the remote peer is behind a restricted-cone NAT that
requires knowing the destination endpoint before it will forward traffic.
.sp
Use
.B passive
for mobile devices or intermittently-connected clients that should
initiate contact themselves.  The server-side daemon will respond to
each client's OFFER so that both NATs are punched before the
WireGuard handshake fires.
.\"
.TP
.B dns-roam
PeerJS is not used.  Instead, the daemon resolves the hostname given
in
.B DnsHost
every poll cycle.  When the resolved address changes it calls
.B "wg set \fIiface\fR peer \fIpubkey\fR endpoint \fIip\fR:\fIport\fR"
and wakes the kernel WireGuard module to trigger a new handshake.
.sp
Use
.B dns-roam
for peers behind dynamic DNS (DDNS) where you control the hostname
but the underlying IP changes unpredictably.
.\"
.TP
.B ignore
The daemon takes no action for this peer.  Useful for upstream VPN
provider tunnels, relay servers, or any peer whose endpoint is
managed by another mechanism.
.\"
.SS "OFFER LOOP PROTECTION"
.\"
When two responsive peers exchange OFFERs continuously without the
tunnel ever coming up (for example because of a symmetric NAT on one
side, or a routing black-hole), the daemon applies the following
safeguards:
.IP \(bu 4
A rate-limit prevents sending more than one outbound OFFER
per 25 seconds per peer, regardless of how many incoming OFFERs arrive.
.IP \(bu 4
A rolling-window counter tracks how many OFFER exchanges occur
within a 10-minute window.  When the counter reaches 8 without the
tunnel recovering, the daemon logs a
.B WARNING
and enters a 5-minute
.I quarantine
for that peer: all responsive OFFERs are suppressed until the
quarantine expires.  This bounds worst-case broker traffic to roughly
one OFFER per 25 seconds during active exchange, falling back to at
most one burst per 15 minutes under a sustained fault.
.IP \(bu 4
If an OFFER arrives bearing this daemon's own routing ID
(which would happen if a host accidentally configures its own public
key in its peers.d file), it is discarded with a
.B WARNING
and never processed.
.PP
After a quarantine period the counter resets and the daemon tries
again.  When the tunnel eventually comes up the counter and quarantine
state are cleared immediately.
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH HOLE-PUNCHING MECHANISM
.\"
The hole-punching sequence, as executed after receiving a valid OFFER,
is:
.IP 1. 4
.B Raw-socket injection.
A raw
.B AF_INET/SOCK_RAW
socket with
.B IP_HDRINCL
sends three empty UDP datagrams to the remote endpoint.  The source
port in the hand-crafted IP+UDP header is set to the local WireGuard
listen port.  This causes the NAT device to create an outbound
mapping from
.RI < local_listen_port >
to
.RI < remote_ip > : < remote_port >
in the NAT table.  The three-packet burst (with a 50 ms gap) hedges
against UDP packet loss during NAT state creation.
.IP
Because the kernel WireGuard module binds the listen port exclusively,
even
.BR SO_REUSEADDR / SO_REUSEPORT
is rejected for that port; the raw socket bypasses this restriction
because it operates at the IP layer, not the UDP layer.
.IP 2. 4
.B Kernel endpoint update.
.B "wg set \fIiface\fR peer \fIpubkey\fR endpoint \fIip\fR:\fIport\fR"
is called to tell the kernel WireGuard module where the remote peer
now lives.
.IP 3. 4
.B Handshake wake.
A 1-byte UDP datagram is sent through the WireGuard interface using
.B SO_BINDTODEVICE
to force it through the correct interface regardless of routing table
preference.  The kernel WireGuard module observes the outbound
traffic, sees a pending handshake for the updated endpoint, and
initiates it.
.sp
For peers with a
.B /32
allowed-ip the datagram is addressed to that host address.  For peers
with a wider subnet the first usable host address is used.  For
.B 0.0.0.0/0
catch-all peers,
.B 192.0.2.1
(TEST-NET-1, RFC 5737) is used; any address in the /0 range would
work, but 192.0.2.1 is unlikely to exist as a real host and is
clearly bogon.
.sp
The conntrack NAT mapping created by the raw injection lasts
approximately 30 seconds (default
.B nf_conntrack_udp_timeout
on Linux).  The wake step must trigger a handshake within this
window; in practice the WireGuard handshake completes in under 1
second.
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH CRYPTOGRAPHY
.\"
All signalling payloads are end-to-end encrypted; the PeerJS broker
sees only opaque blobs and cannot read or modify the endpoint
information.
.SS Key derivation
.PP
For each peer pair (A, B) a shared symmetric key is derived:
.IP 1. 4
Perform X25519 Diffie-Hellman:
.sp
.B shared = X25519(my_wg_private_key, peer_wg_public_key)
.IP 2. 4
Apply keyed BLAKE2b for domain separation:
.sp
.B key = BLAKE2b\-256(shared, key=\(lqwg-peerjs/v1/sigbox\(rq)
.PP
The domain label ensures that this key is cryptographically
independent from WireGuard's own session keys, even though both
derive from the same Curve25519 keypair.
.SS Payload encryption
.PP
Payloads are encrypted with
.B libsodium SecretBox
(XSalsa20-Poly1305).  Each payload contains:
.RS
.TP
.B v
Protocol version (integer, currently 1).  Recipients reject
mismatches.
.TP
.B ts
Unix timestamp of encryption time (integer seconds).  Recipients
reject messages older than 90 seconds or more than 90 seconds in the
future, providing replay protection.
.TP
.B ip
The sender's current public IPv4 address (string).
.TP
.B port
The sender's WireGuard listen port (integer).
.RE
.PP
The encrypted blob is base64-encoded and carried in
.B payload.metadata.blob
of the PeerJS OFFER envelope.
.SS Endpoint validation
.PP
On receipt, the decrypted endpoint is sanity-checked before being
applied to the kernel:
loopback, link-local, multicast, unspecified, and reserved addresses
are rejected.  Port numbers outside 1\(en65535 are rejected.  This
prevents a compromised peer or broker from redirecting WireGuard
handshakes to infrastructure services.
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH PEERJS ROUTING IDENTITY
.\"
Each daemon instance registers on the signalling broker under a
deterministic routing ID derived from its WireGuard public key and the
shared salt:
.PP
.B routing_id = SHA\-256(wg_public_key_bytes || salt_bytes).hexdigest()
.PP
Because the salt is site-specific and not embedded in the public key,
two installations running the same WireGuard key with different salts
will not interfere with each other on the public broker.
.PP
The daemon opens
.I one
long-lived WebSocket connection per process, not one per peer.  This
is deliberate: a single connection is sufficient for all configured peers
(routing IDs are per-peer, not per-connection), and avoids multiplying
broker load with the number of peers.
.PP
The routing ID is keyed to the WireGuard interface whose public key
the daemon chose as the "primary" interface (the one hosting the most
non-IGNORE configured peers).  Peers configured on
.I other
WireGuard interfaces on the same host will not reach this daemon over
PeerJS until multi-interface support is added.  A warning is logged
when this situation is detected.
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH PEERJS WIRE FORMAT
.\"
All signalling messages use the standard PeerJS OFFER wire format: a
WebRTC datachannel OFFER envelope with freshly generated ICE credentials
and a DTLS fingerprint in the SDP body.  The encrypted endpoint blob is
carried in
.B payload.metadata.blob
alongside the standard WebRTC fields.
.PP
This format is used unconditionally — with both self-hosted and public
brokers — so there is one wire format regardless of deployment.
.\"
.SS Discriminator: \fBpayload.metadata.kind\fR
.\"
The
.B kind
field inside
.B payload.metadata
discriminates between three message families that all share the OFFER
envelope:
.TP
.B (absent or "offer")
Ordinary signalling OFFER.  The encrypted blob carries a
.B candidates
list (see below); the receiver applies the first valid candidate to the
kernel WG endpoint and (when the tunnel is DOWN) sends a responsive
OFFER carrying its own endpoint(s).
.TP
.B "signal_wake"
Client-initiated wake.  The encrypted blob carries an
.I empty
.B candidates
list — the sender hasn't claimed an endpoint, it's asking the receiver
to refresh its view.  The receiver does NOT touch kernel WG state from
a wake (no endpoint claim to apply).  It DOES send a responsive OFFER
carrying its own endpoint(s),
.I bypassing the "tunnel-already-UP" guard
that suppresses ordinary responsive OFFERs, since wakes are explicit
user-driven requests.  The same OFFER-loop rate-limiters apply.
.TP
.B "enroll" / "enroll_ok" / "enroll_err"
Auto-enrollment.  See AUTO-ENROLLMENT below.
.\"
.SS Encrypted blob: \fBcandidates\fR list
.\"
The decrypted
.B blob
plaintext is JSON of the form:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
{
  "v": 1, "ts": <epoch_seconds>,
  "candidates": [
    {"ip": "192.168.43.1", "port": 51820, "kind": "lan"},
    {"ip": "1.2.3.4",      "port": 51820, "kind": "stun"}
  ]
}
.fi
.RE
.PP
.B Senders
list candidate endpoints in preference order: a phone in host-mode-on-
hotspot fills
.B [LAN, STUN]
so on-LAN guests pick the LAN candidate without crossing the public IP
(avoiding cellular hairpin-NAT failure).  An ordinary single-endpoint
daemon fills exactly one entry.  Senders that don't claim any endpoint
(today,
.BR signal_wake )
fill an empty list.
.PP
.B Receivers
take the first candidate that passes
.B is_valid_public_endpoint
(rejects loopback, link-local, multicast, unspecified, reserved, and
weirdly-low ports — RFC 1918 private addresses are accepted on the
assumption the sender saw a LAN candidate and the receiver is on the
same LAN).  Kernel WireGuard endpoint roaming sorts out the rest from
real handshake traffic — no need for the receiver to time-share
between candidates.
.PP
.B Per-candidate
.B kind
is purely informational
.RB ( lan / stun / dns / manual ;
future expansion: \fBv6ll\fR, \fBpcp\fR).  Receivers do not interpret
the field; it shows up only in diagnostic logs.
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH AUTO-ENROLLMENT
.\"
Auto-enrollment lets a freshly-installed client join an existing
.B wireguardrtc
mesh by scanning a one-time QR code, with no manual exchange of
public keys.  The protocol is opt-in: enable
.B [Enrollment] Enabled = yes
in the global config and configure
.BR ProvisionScript .
.\"
.SS Threat model
The voucher (token in the QR code) is the trust anchor.  Anyone in
possession of a token can enroll a single device until the token is
consumed or expires.  The protocol guarantees:
.IP \(bu 4
.B Confidentiality.
The PeerJS broker sees only routing IDs and ciphertext.  Endpoint
addresses, name hints, and device strings are encrypted with a key
derived from the token plus an X25519 ECDH between the client's and
server's WireGuard keypairs.
.IP \(bu 4
.B Server authentication.
The encrypted ENROLL_OK / ENROLL_ERR response carries an
authentication tag that only the server (holder of its private
WireGuard key) can produce.  A passive observer cannot forge a
response, and a forged response from any other party fails the
client's auth-tag check.
.IP \(bu 4
.B Single-use enforcement.
The server marks tokens as consumed atomically before invoking the
provisioning hook.  Concurrent racers serialize on a file lock; the
loser receives an authenticated
.B TOKEN_USED
response so the legitimate user
.I notices the failure
rather than silently re-enrolling onto a stolen identity.
.IP \(bu 4
.B Replay safety.
A successful enrollment response is cached server-side for 5 minutes,
keyed by the client's public key.  Legitimate retries (lost
.B ENROLL_OK
over a flaky network) return the same envelope; only the holder of
the matching private key can decrypt it.
.PP
.B What auto-enrollment does NOT protect against:
QR-code leakage.  If an attacker observes the QR before the legitimate
user does, they can race for the token.  In a small-scale deployment
this is acceptable: the loser sees an authenticated
.B TOKEN_USED
error and surfaces a prominent failure to the user, who can then ask
the admin to revoke the rogue enrollment and mint a fresh token.
Treat QR images like one-time passwords — share over E2EE channels
or in person, not via plaintext email.
.\"
.SS Wire format
Both
.B ENROLL
and the corresponding
.B ENROLL_OK
/
.B ENROLL_ERR
responses ride inside the same WebRTC OFFER envelope used by
signalling traffic; they are discriminated by a
.B kind
field inside
.IR payload.metadata :
.IP
.EX
"metadata": {
    "v":          1,
    "kind":       "enroll" | "enroll_ok" | "enroll_err",
    "client_pub": "<X25519 base64>",   // ENROLL only
    "server_pub": "<X25519 base64>",   // ENROLL_OK / ENROLL_ERR only
    "blob":       "<base64 secretbox>"
}
.EE
.IP
The
.B blob
is encrypted under a key derived as:
.IP
.EX
shared     = X25519(local_priv, peer_pub)
enroll_key = BLAKE2b-32(shared,    key="wg-peerjs/v1/enroll")
final_key  = BLAKE2b-32(enroll_key, key=token)
ciphertext = secretbox(plaintext, key=final_key)
.EE
.IP
Domain separation guarantees: the enrollment key cannot collide with
the signalling key (which uses
.IR wg-peerjs/v1/sigbox )
and re-keying with
.B token
binds each ciphertext to a specific single-use voucher.
.\"
.SS URI format
The minted token is encoded as a
.B wgrtc-enroll://v1?\&...
URI suitable for embedding in a QR code:
.IP
.EX
wgrtc-enroll://v1?
    pk=<server_pubkey, b64url no padding>
    &salt=<salt, b64url no padding>
    &broker=<wss-url>
    &brokerkey=<peerjs key>
    &token=<32-byte token, b64url no padding>
    &expires=<unix seconds>
    &server=<NAME>
.EE
.\"
.SS Operations
.B Mint a token (admin):
.IP
.EX
sudo wireguardrtc \-\-enroll\-token "Anna's Pixel 8"
.EE
.IP
Prints the URI on stdout and a terminal QR code (when stdout is a
TTY and
.BR qrencode (1)
is installed).  The daemon must be running for the token to be
processed; the
.B \-\-enroll\-token
mode itself just persists the token to
.I StateDir/pending-tokens.json
and exits.
.\"
.PP
.B Honour an enrollment request (server, automatic):
The running daemon listens for
.B ENROLL
messages on its PeerJS connection.  On receipt:
.IP 1. 4
Try-decrypt the ciphertext against each unexpired token in
.IR pending-tokens.json .
.IP 2. 4
Validate the inner timestamp is within ±90 s of current time.
.IP 3. 4
Atomically claim the token (compare-and-swap under
.BR flock (2)).
.IP 4. 4
Invoke
.B ProvisionScript
with the new peer's
.IR IFACE ,
.IR NAME ,
and base64-encoded public key.
.IP 5. 4
Read back the allocated address via
.BR "wg show \fIIFACE\fR allowed-ips" .
.IP 6. 4
Build, encrypt, and send the
.B ENROLL_OK
response.  Cache it for 5 minutes for retry safety.
.PP
On any failure that the client should
.B notice
(token already consumed, provisioning script error), the daemon sends
an authenticated
.B ENROLL_ERR
response carrying a machine-readable
.B code
field.  On any failure that should
.B not
leak token state (no decryption succeeded — could be wrong key,
no such token, or expired token), the daemon silently drops the
request and logs at
.B WARNING
level on its own side.
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH LIVE KERNEL STATE
.\"
The daemon never parses WireGuard
.I .conf
files.  All peer and interface state is read from the running kernel
via
.B wg show
subcommands:
.RS
.TP
.B wg show interfaces
Enumerate WireGuard interfaces.
.TP
.B wg show \fIiface\fR private-key
Read private key (requires
.BR CAP_NET_ADMIN ).
.TP
.B wg show \fIiface\fR public-key
Read public key.
.TP
.B wg show \fIiface\fR listen-port
Read the bound UDP port.
.TP
.B wg show \fIiface\fR latest-handshakes
Get the last handshake time (Unix seconds) for each peer.
.TP
.B wg show \fIiface\fR endpoints
Get the current kernel endpoint for each peer.
.TP
.B wg show \fIiface\fR allowed-ips
Read the allowed-ip prefixes, used to select a wake target.
.RE
.PP
The state is refreshed every
.B POLL_INTERVAL
seconds (30 s).
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH SIGNALS
.\"
.TP
.BR SIGTERM ", " SIGINT
Initiates a clean shutdown: the PeerJS WebSocket is closed, all
asyncio tasks are cancelled, and the process exits with status 0.
.PP
There is no
.B SIGHUP
reload; restart the daemon with
.B systemctl restart wireguardrtc
to pick up configuration changes.
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH EXIT STATUS
.\"
.TP
.B 0
Clean shutdown (SIGTERM or SIGINT received).
.TP
.B 2
Fatal configuration or capability error:
missing or placeholder Salt;
missing global configuration file;
no usable WireGuard interface found;
cannot create raw socket (missing
.BR CAP_NET_RAW );
cannot read WireGuard private key (missing
.BR CAP_NET_ADMIN );
another instance already holds the lock file;
or a required Python package is not installed.
.PP
Exit status 2 is treated as a permanent failure by the systemd unit
.RB ( RestartPreventExitStatus=2 );
the service will not be restarted automatically until the
administrator corrects the configuration and runs
.BR "systemctl start wireguardrtc" .
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.\"
.TP
.B WIREGUARDRTC_CONFIG_DIR
Overrides the base directory for both the global config file and the
peers directory.  Default:
.IR /etc/wireguardrtc .
Useful for testing without touching system files.
.TP
.B LOG_LEVEL
Default log level, equivalent to
.BR \-\-log\-level .
Respected only when
.B \-\-log\-level
is not given on the command line.
.TP
.B PYTHONUNBUFFERED
Set to
.B 1
by the systemd unit so that log lines are written to the journal
immediately rather than being held in Python's stdio buffer.
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH FILES
.\"
.TP
.I /etc/wireguardrtc/wireguardrtc.conf
Global daemon configuration.  Owned
.BR root : wireguardrtc ,
mode
.BR 0640 .
See
.B CONFIGURATION FILES
above.
.TP
.I /etc/wireguardrtc/peers.d/*.conf
Per-peer drop-in files.  Same ownership and mode as the global
config.  See
.B CONFIGURATION FILES
and
.B PEER MODES
above.
.TP
.I /var/lib/wireguardrtc/auto-enrolled.d/*.conf
Auto-generated per-peer drop-ins, one per successfully-enrolled
peer.  Format identical to
.IR /etc/wireguardrtc/peers.d/*.conf ;
default
.B Mode = active
so the daemon pushes signalling OFFERs to the new peer (Phase-2
endpoint roaming on the Android client relies on this).  Disabled
by setting
.B [Enrollment] AutoActive = no
in
.IR wireguardrtc.conf .
Admin entries in
.I /etc/wireguardrtc/peers.d/
override entries here on
.B PublicKey
collision.
.TP
.I /run/wireguardrtc/lock
Single-instance lock file.  The daemon acquires an exclusive
.BR flock (2)
on this file at startup; subsequent instances exit immediately with
an error.  The directory
.I /run/wireguardrtc
is created by the systemd
.B RuntimeDirectory=wireguardrtc
directive and removed when the service stops.
.TP
.I /usr/sbin/wireguardrtc
The daemon executable.
.TP
.I /usr/sbin/wireguardrtc-key-oracle
The privileged key-derivation oracle.  Holds WireGuard private keys
and serves derive_sigbox/derive_enroll/set_endpoint requests over
.IR /run/wireguardrtc/oracle.sock .
Sole holder of
.B CAP_NET_ADMIN
on the host.
.TP
.I /usr/sbin/wireguardrtc-raw-helper
The privileged raw-socket helper.  Sends the hole-punch inject and
the WG-iface-bound wake-up datagram on validated inputs from the
daemon, over
.IR /run/wireguardrtc/raw.sock .
Sole holder of
.B CAP_NET_RAW
on the host.
.TP
.I /usr/sbin/wireguardrtc-provision-client
Daemon-side hook for the provisioning broker.  Default
.B ProvisionScript
in
.IR wireguardrtc.conf ;
runs in the daemon's sandbox and forwards the request to the broker
over a Unix socket.
.TP
.I /usr/sbin/wireguardrtc-provision-broker
Privileged side of the provisioning channel.  Reads one request from
stdin, validates strictly, invokes the configured Provisioner, writes
the result to stdout.  Not invoked directly by admins \(em started
via socket activation by
.IR wireguardrtc-provision-broker@.service .
.TP
.I /usr/sbin/wireguardrtc-provision-default
Default Provisioner for stock
.BR wg-quick (8)
deployments.  Allocates from a CIDR pool and writes
.B [Peer]
blocks to
.IR /etc/wireguard/IFACE.conf .
Override in
.IR /etc/wireguardrtc/provision-broker.conf .
.TP
.I /etc/wireguardrtc/provision-broker.conf
Names the upstream Provisioner the broker invokes.  See the example
under
.IR /usr/share/doc/wireguardrtc/examples/ .
.TP
.I /etc/wireguardrtc/provisioning.conf
Read by
.B wireguardrtc-provision-default
only.  Defines the CIDR pool for auto-allocated peer addresses.
.TP
.I /run/wireguardrtc-provision/sock
Unix socket the daemon-side client writes provision requests to.
Created by
.IR wireguardrtc-provision-broker.socket
on first request.
.TP
.IR /var/lib/wireguardrtc-provision-broker/permits/<urlsafe_token>
Single-use permit dropped by
.B wireguardrtc \-\-enroll\-token
when an admin mints a token; consumed by the broker on first
provisioning request that matches.  Mode
.BR 0700 ,
root-owned; the daemon process cannot write here, which is what gates
provisioning to the actual mint→consumption window.
.TP
.I /lib/systemd/system/wireguardrtc.service
systemd unit file for the daemon.
.TP
.I /lib/systemd/system/wireguardrtc-provision-broker.socket
.TQ
.I /lib/systemd/system/wireguardrtc-provision-broker@.service
systemd socket and per-connection service template for the broker.
Enable with
.BR "systemctl enable --now wireguardrtc-provision-broker.socket"
when auto-enrollment is in use.
.TP
.I /usr/share/man/man8/wireguardrtc.8.gz
This manual page.
.TP
.I /usr/share/doc/wireguardrtc/examples/peers.d/
Example per-peer drop-in files (active-peer.conf, passive-mobile.conf,
dns-roam.conf).  Copy and edit as needed.
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH SECURITY
.\"
.SS Privilege model
The package ships three services with carefully partitioned
capabilities.  The daemon process holds
.B no
capabilities at all; both
.B CAP_NET_ADMIN
and
.B CAP_NET_RAW
live in tiny sibling helpers that the daemon talks to over Unix
sockets.
.TP
.B wireguardrtc.service
The main daemon — receives PeerJS messages, decrypts OFFERs,
dispatches enrollment, runs the polling loop.  Runs as the
.B wireguardrtc
user with
.B no Linux capabilities .
After RCE on the daemon a kernel-level privileged syscall is rejected
outright; the daemon can only issue narrow RPCs to its helpers,
each of which validates inputs.
.TP
.B wireguardrtc-key-oracle.service
Holds the WireGuard private keys.  Runs as the
.B wireguardrtc
user with
.B CAP_NET_ADMIN
only.  Serves three RPCs over
.IR /run/wireguardrtc/oracle.sock :
.RS
.IP \(bu 4
.BR derive_sigbox " (\fIiface, peer_pub\fR) -> 32-byte signalling key"
.IP \(bu 4
.BR derive_enroll " (\fIiface, peer_pub, token\fR) -> 32-byte enrollment key"
.IP \(bu 4
.BR set_endpoint " (\fIiface, peer_pub, ip, port\fR) -> bool"
\(em refuses to silently create new peers (peer must already be in
.IR allowed-ips ),
refuses loopback / link-local / multicast / reserved IPs, refuses
ports outside 1..65535
.RE
.IP
The raw 32-byte private key never leaves this process, so an RCE on
the daemon cannot lift it for use against the host's WireGuard mesh
identity.
.TP
.B wireguardrtc-raw-helper.service
Holds
.B CAP_NET_RAW
for the spoofy operations the protocol needs.  Runs as the
.B wireguardrtc
user.  Serves two RPCs over
.IR /run/wireguardrtc/raw.sock :
.RS
.IP \(bu 4
.BR inject " (\fIiface, src_port, dst_ip, dst_port\fR) -> bool"
\(em sends the 3-packet hole-punch burst with spoofed source port.
Refuses if
.I src_port
doesn't match the iface's actual listen-port from
.BR "wg show" ,
or if
.I dst_ip
fails the same loopback/link-local/multicast/reserved check the
daemon used to apply.
.IP \(bu 4
.BR wake " (\fIiface, target_ip\fR) -> bool"
\(em sends one zero-byte UDP via
.B SO_BINDTODEVICE
on the WG iface so kernel WG triggers a handshake.  Permits
RFC 5737 documentation IPs because
.I target_ip
is consumed by kernel WG (which encrypts before egress) and has no
exfiltration potential.
.RE
.IP
After RCE on the daemon an attacker can ask this helper to inject
spoofed packets, but only to publicly-routable IPs and only with the
host's own WireGuard listen-port as source.
.TP
.B wireguardrtc-key-oracle.service
The privileged key-derivation oracle.  Reads private keys from the
kernel via
.BR "wg show \fIiface\fR private-key" ,
holds them in memory, and serves a small JSON-RPC interface
.RB ( derive_sigbox ,
.BR derive_enroll ,
.BR set_endpoint )
over a Unix socket at
.IR /run/wireguardrtc/oracle.sock
to the daemon.  Runs as the same
.B wireguardrtc
user with:
.RS
.IP \(bu 4
.B CAP_NET_ADMIN
\(em sole purpose: read private keys and call
.BR "wg set" .
.RE
.IP
The oracle never opens an internet socket, never reads
.IR /etc ,
and is heavily seccomp-filtered (same
.B @system-service
profile as the daemon, but without
.BR @debug ).
The daemon process therefore cannot
.BR ptrace (2)
the oracle to lift keys out of its address space, even though both
processes run as the same user.
.PP
The recommended deployment uses the static system user
.B wireguardrtc
(created by the Debian package's
.B postinst
script) and grants only the two required capabilities via
.BR AmbientCapabilities .
The configuration directory
.I /etc/wireguardrtc
is owned
.BR root : wireguardrtc
with mode
.B 0750
so that the daemon user can read it but unprivileged users cannot
access the salt (which is sensitive: it determines the routing
identity on the shared signalling broker).
.SS Signalling security
The PeerJS broker is treated as an untrusted relay.
All endpoint information is encrypted with
.B SecretBox
before transmission; the broker cannot learn the IP address or port
of any peer, and cannot forge or replay endpoint updates (the freshness
window is \(+-90 seconds).
.PP
Two different installations that share the same WireGuard key pair but
use different salts are cryptographically isolated on the broker: their
routing IDs will not collide, and their payloads are encrypted under
different derived keys.
.SS Endpoint acceptance
Received endpoints are validated to reject loopback, link-local,
multicast, unspecified, and reserved addresses before being applied
to the kernel.  This limits the impact of a key compromise: a
compromised peer cannot redirect WireGuard handshakes to
infrastructure services such as cloud metadata endpoints.
.SS Auto-enrollment privilege separation
The daemon is the only component directly exposed to internet traffic
(via the PeerJS WebSocket and the kernel WireGuard endpoint), so its
RCE blast radius is the dominant attack-surface concern.  Auto-enroll
provisioning would otherwise let a compromised daemon write arbitrary
.B [Peer]
blocks into
.IR /etc/wireguard/ ,
persisting backdoor peers across daemon restarts.  The package
mitigates this with a privilege-separated broker
.B and
a per-mint permit so the broker only accepts requests when an
auto-enrollment is actively in progress:
.IP \(bu 4
The daemon's
.B ProvisionScript
points at
.IR /usr/sbin/wireguardrtc-provision-client ,
a small wrapper that runs inside the daemon's sandbox and never
touches
.IR /etc/wireguard .
.IP \(bu 4
The client connects to
.IR /run/wireguardrtc-provision/sock ,
a Unix socket created by
.B wireguardrtc-provision-broker.socket
(mode 0660, group
.BR wireguardrtc ).
.IP \(bu 4
.B wireguardrtc-provision-broker@.service
is socket-activated, runs as root with
.B CAP_NET_ADMIN
only (other root capabilities dropped via
.BR CapabilityBoundingSet ),
and is reinstantiated per request.  It strictly validates the
.IR (iface, name, pubkey, token)
tuple it receives \(em
.I iface
must match
.IR ^wg[0-9]+(p[0-9]+)?$ ,
.I name
must match
.IR [\\w\ .'\-]{1,64}
(Unicode letters/digits/underscore plus space, dot, apostrophe,
hyphen \(em deliberately permissive enough for "Anna's Pixel 8" and
similar real-world names),
.I pubkey
must be 44-char standard base64 decoding to exactly 32 bytes,
.I token
must be 43-char URL-safe base64 decoding to exactly 32 bytes \(em then
invokes the configured Provisioner (default
.IR /usr/sbin/wireguardrtc-provision-default ;
override in
.IR /etc/wireguardrtc/provision-broker.conf ).
.IP \(bu 4
.B Permit gating.
For every minted token,
.B wireguardrtc \-\-enroll\-token
also drops a single-use permit file in
.IR /var/lib/wireguardrtc-provision-broker/permits/<urlsafe_token> ,
in a directory the daemon process cannot write to (mode
.BR 0700 ,
root-owned).  The broker requires a matching permit to be present
before invoking the Provisioner; the permit is unlinked before
provisioning runs (single-use enforced even if the Provisioner
fails).  Effect: outside the window between mint and consumption,
broker requests are flatly refused \(em a daemon RCE cannot synthesize
a permit because it has no write access to the directory, and cannot
provision peers at all without a corresponding admin-issued mint.
.IP \(bu 4
After RCE on the daemon an attacker can attempt to hijack an
in-flight enrollment by racing the legitimate broker call with their
own pubkey under the same name, but they cannot provision out of band,
cannot read existing configuration, cannot modify peers other than via
the validated path, and cannot gain shell access.  The legitimate
client whose token was hijacked receives an authenticated
.B TOKEN_USED
response, so the failure is user-noticeable per
.B "Threat model"
above.  The broker's request shape is the entire RPC surface.
.PP
This is the same privsep pattern OpenSSH uses to keep the
network-facing
.B sshd
process from holding the host private key directly.  The companion
.BR wireguardrtc-key-oracle.service
applies the same pattern to the WireGuard private keys themselves
(see
.B Privilege model
above).
.SS Limitations
.IP \(bu 4
.B Symmetric NAT is not supported.
Only cone-NAT topologies (full-cone, address-restricted,
port-restricted) are traversable.  Symmetric NAT requires port
prediction, which the daemon does not implement.
.IP \(bu 4
.B IPv6 hole-punching is not implemented.
The raw injection path constructs an IPv4 header only.  Endpoint
discovery and publication over IPv6 is on the project roadmap but
not yet implemented.
.IP \(bu 4
.B Single interface limitation.
The daemon currently registers a single PeerJS routing ID keyed to one
WireGuard interface.  Peers configured on other WireGuard interfaces
on the same host will not be reachable via PeerJS until multi-interface
support is added.
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH TIMING CONSTANTS
.\"
The following timing constants are compiled into the daemon.  They are
not configurable without editing the source.
.PP
.TS
l l lx.
Constant	Value	Purpose
_
POLL_INTERVAL	30 s	T{
Interval between poll cycles
T}
HANDSHAKE_DEAD_THRESHOLD	180 s	T{
Tunnel considered dead after this
T}
SIGNALING_BACKOFF	300 s	T{
Minimum time between OFFERs per peer
T}
PEERJS_HEARTBEAT	5 s	T{
WebSocket HEARTBEAT cadence
T}
STUN_TIMEOUT	2.5 s	T{
Per-server STUN query timeout
T}
RAW_INJECT_REPEATS	3	T{
Raw-inject burst count
T}
RAW_INJECT_GAP	50 ms	T{
Delay between burst packets
T}
PROTOCOL_FRESHNESS_WINDOW	90 s	T{
Replay protection window (\(+-)
T}
.TE
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH DIAGNOSTICS
.\"
The daemon logs to standard output / the journal.  Anti-spam filtering
is applied via the internal
.B StateLogger:
each
.IR "(scope, key, value)"
triple is logged only once per value transition.  This means a
persistently-dead tunnel generates one log line when it enters the
dead state, not one line every 30 seconds.
.PP
Useful diagnostic commands:
.PP
.EX
# Follow the live log under systemd
journalctl \-fu wireguardrtc

# Verify WireGuard handshakes are occurring
wg show wg0 latest\-handshakes

# Confirm raw-injected packets reach the wire
tcpdump \-i any udp port 51820

# Check capability grant
systemctl show wireguardrtc \-p AmbientCapabilities

# Check effective config directory
systemctl show wireguardrtc \-p Environment
.EE
.PP
Common warnings and their meaning:
.TP
.B "OFFER from \fIlabel\fR: decryption/freshness failed"
The OFFER arrived but could not be decrypted or its timestamp was
outside the freshness window.  Possible causes: clock skew >90 s
between peers, mismatched WireGuard keys, or a replayed OFFER.
.TP
.B "rejected suspicious peer endpoint \fIip\fR:\fIport\fR"
The decrypted payload contained a loopback, link-local, multicast, or
otherwise disallowed address.
.TP
.B "cannot create raw socket \(em daemon needs CAP_NET_RAW"
The daemon is running without
.BR CAP_NET_RAW .
Enable it with
.B AmbientCapabilities=CAP_NET_RAW
in the systemd unit, or run as root.
.TP
.B "non-IGNORE peers configured on multiple interfaces"
Peers on more than one WireGuard interface are configured.  Only the
primary interface's peers can be reached via PeerJS.  See
.BR BUGS .
.TP
.B "\fIlabel\fR: PublicKey \fIXXX\fR not present on any WireGuard interface"
A drop-in file references a public key that is not present in the live
kernel state.  Check for typos or ensure the WireGuard interface is up.
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH EXAMPLES
.\"
.SS Basic setup (two hosts)
.PP
On
.B both
hosts, generate a shared salt (use the exact same value everywhere):
.PP
.EX
head \-c 32 /dev/urandom | base64
.EE
.PP
Add it to
.I /etc/wireguardrtc/wireguardrtc.conf
on both hosts:
.PP
.EX
[Global]
Salt = <paste\-your\-shared\-salt\-here>
.EE
.PP
On the host that should actively maintain the tunnel, create
.IR /etc/wireguardrtc/peers.d/laptop-anna.conf :
.PP
.EX
[Peer]
PublicKey = <base64\-public\-key\-of\-anna>
Mode = active
.EE
.PP
On Anna's laptop (passive end), create
.IR /etc/wireguardrtc/peers.d/office\-server.conf :
.PP
.EX
[Peer]
PublicKey = <base64\-public\-key\-of\-server>
Mode = passive
.EE
.PP
Restart the daemon on both hosts after editing any configuration file:
.PP
.EX
systemctl restart wireguardrtc
.EE
.\"
.SS DNS roaming
.PP
For a home server behind a DDNS hostname, no broker involvement is
needed.  Create
.IR /etc/wireguardrtc/peers.d/home\-server.conf :
.PP
.EX
[Peer]
PublicKey = <base64\-public\-key\-of\-home\-server>
Mode = dns-roam
DnsHost = home.example.com:51820
.EE
.PP
The daemon will resolve
.I home.example.com
every 30 seconds and update the WireGuard endpoint when the IP
changes.
.\"
.SS Private broker
.PP
For deployments that want to avoid the public broker:
.PP
.EX
# On a host with Docker:
docker run \-d \-\-name peerjs \-\-restart=always \-p 9000:9000 \\
    peerjs/peerjs\-server \-\-port 9000 \-\-key mysecretkey
.EE
.PP
Then in
.IR /etc/wireguardrtc/wireguardrtc.conf :
.PP
.EX
[Global]
PeerJsServer = ws://broker.example.com:9000/peerjs
PeerJsKey = mysecretkey
.EE
.\"
.SS Testing without system paths
.PP
.EX
export WIREGUARDRTC_CONFIG_DIR=$HOME/wg\-test
sudo wireguardrtc \-\-log\-level DEBUG
.EE
.\"
